1773968014994147	command-lattice-dev	itc:v3:AWKTkyTOeZ5M5QAAAAAAQa61bvb1ugAAAAEvAw		item.create	bn-397	{"description":"## Problem\n\nSeveral `msh remote` subcommands that take positional float args reject negative values because clap interprets leading `-` as a flag:\n\n```\n$ msh remote set-light-dir -0.5 1.0 0.3\nerror: unexpected argument '-0' found\n  tip: to pass '-0' as a value, use '-- -0'\n```\n\nWorkaround exists (`-- -0.5 1.0 0.3`) but it's not ergonomic and easy to forget.\n\n## Affected commands\n\nAny remote subcommand with positional float args where negative values are valid:\n- `set-light-dir <X> <Y> <Z>`\n- `camera-pos <X> <Y> <Z>`\n- `camera-target <X> <Y> <Z>`\n- `set-clear-color <R> <G> <B> <A>` (less likely but technically possible)\n\n## Fix\n\nUse `#[arg(allow_negative_numbers = true)]` on the positional args in the clap structs, or `#[command(allow_negative_numbers = true)]` on the subcommand struct. This tells clap to accept values that look like negative numbers.\n\n## Context\n\nDiscovered while testing the RPC flow for the command-lattice sprite_gen pipeline. Light direction needs negative components for top-left lighting.","kind":"bug","title":"remote subcommands reject negative float args (set-light-dir, camera-pos, etc.)"}	blake3:pmHdVNQsutnBVL3qshh3WivZI7EfIR6eMZzYJoCWGW0
1773968059952234	msh-dev	itc:v3:AWLzMzyc5k_JEAAAAAAAQfbb13a_UAAAAAEtUA		item.move	bn-397	{"state":"doing"}	blake3:buPJmtNnS5QT0iNBlYi5xwObmnaReBSgDWeEIjDhalo
1773968059956463	msh-dev	itc:v3:AWLzMzyc5k_JEAAAAAAAQfbb13a_UAAAAAEtUQ		item.assign	bn-397	{"action":"assign","agent":"msh-dev"}	blake3:qKY1x3GB8hBOqQujAhIDhrIti_122LfpZSBmsBGACEs
1773968160863389	msh-dev	itc:v3:AWLzMzyc5k_JEAAAAAAAQfbb13a_UAAAAAEtUg		item.move	bn-397	{"state":"done"}	blake3:qSzYDwxF95j9Hk79I1n846D4Hbj4MZ-WqDvAWlamA00
1773977242418647	command-lattice-dev	itc:v3:AWKTkyTOeZ5M5QAAAAAAQa61bvb1ugAAAAEvBA		item.create	bn-21w	{"description":"## Problem\n\nmsh currently renders all geometry with a single `set_base_color`. There's no way to load a mesh with multiple colors/materials and have them render distinctly.\n\nThis blocks the command-lattice sprite_gen pipeline from producing multi-colored assets (e.g., buildings with colored walls + gray roof details, or resource nodes with distinct base/crystal colors).\n\n## Desired behavior\n\nWhen loading a mesh that has material/color information, msh should render each face group with its assigned color instead of the global base color. Two viable paths:\n\n### Option A: OBJ + MTL support\nOBJ files can reference a `.mtl` sidecar with `Kd` (diffuse color) per material. Faces are assigned to materials via `usemtl` directives. This is the simplest format to generate from sprite_gen.\n\n### Option B: GLB material support\nGLB/glTF already encodes PBR materials with base color. msh loads GLB but currently ignores material colors. Honoring `baseColorFactor` from the material would enable colored meshes.\n\n### Option C: Vertex colors\nSome formats (PLY, extended OBJ) support per-vertex colors. Less useful for flat-shaded sprite baking.\n\n## Recommendation\n\nOption A (OBJ + MTL) is probably simplest since msh already loads OBJ. OpenSCAD can't export MTL directly, but sprite_gen can generate the .mtl sidecar alongside the .obj when converting from OFF.\n\n## Context\n\nDiscovered during command-lattice sprite_gen development. Currently working around this with single-color renders per asset kind.","kind":"task","title":"Support per-material/per-face colors from OBJ .mtl or GLB materials"}	blake3:yWfPeF_qhfUbgiZb241wIt5jw0SSogaERXylb_n9KtY
1774057923692159	msh-dev	itc:v3:AWLzMzyc5k_JEAAAAAAAQfbb13a_UAAAAAEtUw		item.move	bn-21w	{"state":"doing"}	blake3:lTcxVdiYj62n8OWoDk3fESdfL4R0bAtSxWL5ii_2vxw
1774057923698405	msh-dev	itc:v3:AWLzMzyc5k_JEAAAAAAAQfbb13a_UAAAAAEtVA		item.assign	bn-21w	{"action":"assign","agent":"msh-dev"}	blake3:z64-OfnNaO36PVsrQyglnLBpJ3Ax46FY_Y6kZKRBI2w
1774058471833606	msh-dev	itc:v3:AWLzMzyc5k_JEAAAAAAAQfbb13a_UAAAAAEtVQ		item.move	bn-21w	{"state":"done"}	blake3:AmIlEYCTpaonimiyl7zmBxY5CL2Oe4M4hnz8l_rmQyM
1774107764550529	msh-dev	itc:v3:AWLzMzyc5k_JEAAAAAAAQfbb13a_UAAAAAEtVg		item.create	bn-222	{"description":"## Problem\n\nmsh doesn't support .3mf files. The format is increasingly common (Bambu Studio, PrusaSlicer, Windows 3D Builder all export it) and natively supports per-triangle colors via color groups — useful for the sprite_gen pipeline.\n\n## Approach\n\nAdd a .3mf loader to mesh/loader.rs. The format is a ZIP archive containing XML (3D/3dmodel.model). Parse vertices, triangles, and optional colorgroup/colorid attributes for per-face colors.\n\nDependencies: zip + quick-xml (with serde feature) for extraction and XML parsing.\n\nFits directly into the existing MeshWithColors struct.\n\n## Scope\n\n- Parse .3mf geometry (vertices + triangles)\n- Extract per-triangle colors from colorgroup definitions\n- Wire into load_mesh_with_colors() and load_mesh() paths\n- Add \"3mf\" to the extension match in both functions","kind":"task","title":"Support .3mf file loading with per-triangle colors"}	blake3:m97W_HBUkwsLFpishnVG0Lc5DNNUUJGCanZbXZZLcr0
1774107767402793	msh-dev	itc:v3:AWLzMzyc5k_JEAAAAAAAQfbb13a_UAAAAAEtVw		item.move	bn-222	{"state":"doing"}	blake3:-ftdi5dX_ETCr-9VWGpoEd2dYLIIaopXI0WBy-So5rE
1774107767413150	msh-dev	itc:v3:AWLzMzyc5k_JEAAAAAAAQfbb13a_UAAAAAEtWA		item.assign	bn-222	{"action":"assign","agent":"msh-dev"}	blake3:gWVbLQmF11Ip-8574dH17Bcef5OVVf5fjsMirHGbeA8
1774107884913050	msh-dev	itc:v3:AWLzMzyc5k_JEAAAAAAAQfbb13a_UAAAAAEtWQ		item.move	bn-222	{"state":"done"}	blake3:dWToh7YPu39K_TgdTf2SunY56lHhinmg9kV_i_yV2qk
1774108702951715	command-lattice-dev	itc:v3:AWKTkyTOeZ5M5QAAAAAAQa61bvb1ugAAAAEvBQ		item.create	bn-2pz	{"description":"## Problem\n\nWhen loading a 3MF file that has `color()` assignments from OpenSCAD, all geometry renders with the global base_color. The per-object colors from the 3MF are not applied.\n\n## Repro\n\n```scad\n$fn = 12;\ncolor([0.3, 0.5, 0.9]) cube([1.2, 1.2, 0.6], center=true);\ncolor([0.8, 0.2, 0.2]) translate([0.3, 0.3, 0.35]) cylinder(h=0.4, r=0.12);\ncolor([0.2, 0.7, 0.3]) translate([-0.35, 0, 0.05]) cylinder(h=0.3, r=0.15);\n```\n\nExport: `openscad -o test.3mf test.scad`\nLoad: `msh view test.3mf` → all gray, no per-object colors visible\n\n## Expected\n\nEach object should render with its assigned color (blue body, red tower, green tank).\n\n## Context\n\n3MF stores per-object colors in the XML metadata. OpenSCAD's `color()` calls are preserved in 3MF export. This is the key value of 3MF over OFF/STL for the command-lattice sprite_gen pipeline — colored buildings/assets.","kind":"bug","title":"3MF loader ignores per-object/per-material colors"}	blake3:UCWsiF1UtWbwMs6f9IcF3dow-vFV3SPyWKV6q603xnY
1774108713759959	command-lattice-dev	itc:v3:AWKTkyTOeZ5M5QAAAAAAQa61bvb1ugAAAAEvBg		item.create	bn-21o	{"description":"## Problem\n\n3MF files from OpenSCAD use Z-up coordinate convention. msh uses Y-up. When loading a 3MF, the geometry appears sideways — the vertical axis (Z in OpenSCAD) maps to Z in msh instead of Y.\n\nThe same issue existed with OFF files; sprite_gen currently works around it by swapping Y↔Z during OFF→OBJ conversion.\n\n## Expected\n\nmsh should detect Z-up convention in 3MF files and automatically convert to Y-up, or provide a flag (`--z-up`) to trigger the conversion.\n\n## Context\n\nOpenSCAD always uses Z-up. This affects both OFF and 3MF imports. Currently worked around in sprite_gen's OFF→OBJ converter but not applicable to direct 3MF loading.","kind":"bug","title":"3MF/OFF loader should convert Z-up to Y-up"}	blake3:a2pRBLY3POflDG4LvPaywnHpFE_L0hMi7ICDmuQ5QgA
1774108887739436	msh-dev	itc:v3:AWLzMzyc5k_JEAAAAAAAQfbb13a_UAAAAAEtWg		item.update	bn-2pz	{"field":"description","value":"## Status: Not a msh bug\n\nOpenSCAD 2021.01 (stable) does NOT export colors in 3MF. It performs an implicit union() that merges all objects into a single mesh and discards color() data entirely. The resulting 3MF has no colorgroup, basematerials, or pid/p1 attributes.\n\nColor export only exists in OpenSCAD **nightly builds** with `--enable lazy-union` and `-O export-3mf/material-type=color`. Even then, it's buggy (see openscad/openscad#5994, #6060).\n\nWhen nightly OpenSCAD does export colors, it uses `<m:colorgroup>` / `<m:color>` elements — which msh already parses correctly.\n\n## Workarounds\n- Use OpenSCAD nightly with lazy-union\n- Use ColorSCAD or pycolorscad to export separate STLs and reassemble into colored 3MF\n- Export as separate OBJ+MTL per color group"}	blake3:tdYXG5iU5eXAkY1qJbSSSczSWnuGK60h9-bhrogJlFk
1774108893490107	msh-dev	itc:v3:AWLzMzyc5k_JEAAAAAAAQfbb13a_UAAAAAEtWw		item.move	bn-2pz	{"state":"done"}	blake3:xSVPsh449M6ZPsQgTh7SrTQtqcAXXlfMgpbhP7QYvSI
1774108898771267	msh-dev	itc:v3:AWLzMzyc5k_JEAAAAAAAQfbb13a_UAAAAAEtXA		item.move	bn-21o	{"state":"doing"}	blake3:pxZrUMP1Lh0dGDYuPv9hNRUfxe3upBwjIll4Uw_FMCo
1774108898775113	msh-dev	itc:v3:AWLzMzyc5k_JEAAAAAAAQfbb13a_UAAAAAEtXQ		item.assign	bn-21o	{"action":"assign","agent":"msh-dev"}	blake3:jT3D38CpYhtzVDp5jC0UNCFAtn3Jh232hqkJqvRUyu0
1774109022569728	msh-dev	itc:v3:AWLzMzyc5k_JEAAAAAAAQfbb13a_UAAAAAEtXg		item.move	bn-21o	{"state":"done"}	blake3:-_B0OmA6cCC3xeg2I3L-GDhs4mrAt22jW5RCEKrNqtU
1774110012703186	command-lattice-dev	itc:v3:AWKTkyTOeZ5M5QAAAAAAQa61bvb1ugAAAAEvBw		item.create	bn-e46	{"description":"## Problem\n\nmsh loads material colors from GLB files (log says \"with material colors\") but the rendering shader always uses the global `base_color` uniform. Per-material colors are never displayed.\n\n## Repro\n\nCreate a GLB with multiple materials (via Blender):\n- Gray slab (diffuse_color 0.4, 0.4, 0.4)\n- Blue body (0.3, 0.5, 0.9)\n- Red tower (0.8, 0.2, 0.2)\n\nLoad in msh: `msh view test.glb` → all geometry renders with default gray base_color. No per-object colors visible.\n\n## Expected\n\nWhen a mesh has per-material colors, `lit` and `flat` shading modes should use those colors instead of the global `base_color`. The `set-base-color` RPC should override this when explicitly called, but the default should respect the loaded materials.\n\n## Implementation idea\n\nThe per-primitive material colors could be passed as per-vertex colors in the vertex buffer. The shader would check for vertex color presence and use it instead of the uniform when available. Or add a `material` shading mode that reads from the vertex color attribute.\n\n## Context\n\nThis is the last blocker for multi-colored sprite baking in command-lattice. The Blender→GLB→msh pipeline works for geometry; only the color rendering is missing.\n\nTest file: ~/test_colored_joined.glb","kind":"bug","title":"Render per-material colors from GLB/3MF instead of global base_color"}	blake3:B-YmpqW_gw40eAJ3-pYHwdeVJxcflDp7uRffBlKm0Go
1774110166542850	msh-dev	itc:v3:AWLzMzyc5k_JEAAAAAAAQfbb13a_UAAAAAEtXw		item.update	bn-e46	{"field":"description","value":"## Not a loader bug — test file issue\n\nThe test GLB (test_colored_joined.glb) has 4 named materials (Gray, Blue, Red, Green) but ALL have identical baseColorFactor=[0.8, 0.8, 0.8, 1.0] in the PBR data. The actual colors were never baked into the GLB during Blender export — likely the Principled BSDF Base Color input wasn't connected to the viewport diffuse color.\n\nmsh correctly reads baseColorFactor from each primitive's material and assigns per-vertex colors. The loader, shader, and rendering pipeline all work correctly — verified with the colored_cube.3mf test and OBJ+MTL tests.\n\n## To fix the test file\nIn Blender, ensure each material's Principled BSDF 'Base Color' input is set to the desired color (not just the viewport display color), then re-export as GLB."}	blake3:PDKokWI1L_9YpxMK1oD2OyZ-sF5_RAQ0NUc9oMWGAPI
